Introduction to (Competitive) Pokémon

Pokémon: The Research Question

This analysis will use data from the most popular Over-Used category of Pokémon battles on Pokémon Showdown for Generation IV battles to analyse which Pokémon are the most competitively feasible options for new players embarking on their first Pokémon adventure in Sinnoh. At its core, this project aims to answer the following research question: \[\text{How do the type, role and Generation affect the number of appearances that two Pokémon share with each other in a team?}\]

In the words of Professor Oak from the first Pokémon games, a world of dreams and adventures with Pokémon awaits! Let’s go! 1

The Competitive Network: Data Retrieval

Data from Pokémon Showdown battles using Generation IV Pokémon in November were retrieved from their public server. For this analysis, battles in the Over-Used tier with at least 1760 Elo’o were chosen to focus on the most competitive and popular category for Pokémon battles. The threshold for including partnerships has been set at the 3rd quartile, i.e., edges denote that Pokémon X and Y were among the Top 25% partnerships in the competitive categories 2.

The network created based on these considerations is both directed and weighted while consisting of 51 vertices and 320 edges.

Base Statistics and Damage Categories

The indices for classification can be computed as follows: a Sweeper has higher Offensive Score than Defensive Score (opposite for Walls); the higher attribute between the Physical and Special stat determine its category classification: \[ \text{Offensive Score }_i = \frac{\max(\text{Attack} , \text{ Sp. Attack} ) + \text{Speed}}{2} \] \[ \text{Defensive Score }_i = \frac{\max(\text{Defense}, \text{ Sp. Defense}) + \text{HP}}{2} \]

The Pokémon in the network are plotted below such that the quadrant corresponds to the role, i.e. Quadrant 1 (in top-right) contains Special Sweepers and so on for the other roles as well. Colors denote Pokémon types whereas size represent the relative usage across battles.

Attribute data obtained from user Armgilles on Github

Colorscheme from user APaleSlimGhose on Github

Hypotheses

Similar traits are counterproductive in Pokémon teams and heterophily should be present in the networks as Pokémon connect to others who can counter threats. That being said, since these remakes carry nostalgia, teams may be built around Pokémon from the same generations. Hence, homophily may exist among Pokémon who were introduced in the same generation.

Network Analysis

Network Initialization and Basic Visualization

Having extensively discussed the mechanics in competitive Pokémon, the network for competitive Pokémon in the Over-Used category for November 2021 can finally be visualized. Recall that tie between Pokémon X and Pokémon Y in this network indicates that the partnership between these Pokémon ranks among top quartile.

Fundamental Characteristics

Hence, Tyranitar, Jirachi and Latias are the most popular partners across teams whereas three main communities exist that were built using a WalkTrap algorithm chosen due to compatiblity with weighted graphs with step-size at default=4 as recommended by Pons and Lapaty 3.

Multiple Regression Quadratic Assignment Procedure (MQARP)

# Model 1: Same Generation (naive model using only Generation)
Model      <- list(sameGen    = sameGen)
result1    <- sna::netlm(apps_network, Model)

# Adjusted R-squared: 0.00781 
#              *  Estimate   *  Pr(>=|b|)  *
# ******************************************
# (intercept)  *  18.515216  *  0.000      *
# sameGen      *  -8.197961  *  0.054*     *


# Model 2: Same Role, Type and Generation (competitive model)
Model[[2]] <- sameType
Model[[3]] <- sameRole
result2    <- sna::netlm(apps_network, Model)

# Adjusted R-squared: 0.007085 
#              *  Estimate    *  Pr(>=|b|)  *
# *******************************************
# (intercept)  *  18.6872492  *  0.000      *
# sameGen      *  -8.1904564  *  0.058*     *
# sameType     *   0.4481490  *  0.915      *
# sameRole     *  -0.5212931  *  0.773      *



# Model 3: Legendary Status; Same Role, Type and Generation
Model[[4]] <- Legendary
Model[[5]] <- Legendary %>% t()
result3    <- sna::netlm(apps_network, Model)

# Adjusted R-squared: 0.0496
#              *  Estimate    *  Pr(>=|b|)  *
# *******************************************  
# (intercept)  *  13.7485409  *  0.000      *
# sameGen      *  -7.6251750  *  0.059*     *
# sameType     *  -0.4599335  *  0.893      *
# sameRole     *  -0.5537914  *  0.791      *
# Legendary    *  18.0355946  *  0.036**    *
# LegendaryT   *  18.0355946  *  0.027**    *

Thus, based on the MRQAP regressions, the number of joint appearances among the Top 25% Pokemon partnerships is significantly affected on the dyad level by the Pokémon belonging to the same Generation in a negative manner (contrary to the null hypothesis). This result was significant at 10% significance level in all three model configurations and is small compared to appearances’ distribution within the network, which is right-tailed with median around 40.

In terms of monadic properties, the regression found that Legendary Pokémon are more likely to have higher appearance counts as per the 3rd model configuration with a result that is significant at \(\alpha = 0.05\), The coefficient suggests that legendary Pokémon will have around 18 more appearances than their common counterparts; this is most likely due to their higher base stats that increases their popularity in competitions.

Lastly, all three models have rather low adjusted R-square values; however, the including the Legendary variable in last configuration substantially raises the R-squared value from less than 0.01 to almost 0.05.
